To make a COM class async, you can use the `async` and `await` keywords in combination with Task-based asynchronous programming. Here's an example of how you can modify a COM class to make its methods async assuming it has methods `isconnected`, `connect`, and `do`:

```csharp
using System.Threading.Tasks;

public class MyComClass
{
    // Assuming the COM class has a property or method to check if it's connected
    public bool IsConnected { get; set; }

    // Assuming the COM class has a method to establish a connection
    public void Connect()
    {
        // Connect to the COM device here
        IsConnected = true;
    }

    // Assuming the COM class has a method to perform some action
    public void Do()
    {
        // Perform the action here
    }

    // Modified version of the Connect method to make it async
    public async Task ConnectAsync()
    {
        await Task.Run(() =>
        {
            Connect();
        });
    }

    // Modified version of the Do method to make it async
    public async Task DoAsync()
    {
        await Task.Run(() =>
        {
            Do();
        });
    }
}
```

In this example, the `ConnectAsync` and `DoAsync` methods are modified to be async. They use the `Task.Run` method to run the original synchronous methods (`Connect` and `Do`) on a separate thread, allowing them to be awaited asynchronously.

You can then use these async methods like this:

```csharp
MyComClass comObject = new MyComClass();

// Check if the COM object is connected asynchronously
bool isConnected = await comObject.IsConnectedAsync();

// Connect to the COM object asynchronously
await comObject.ConnectAsync();

// Perform some action on the COM object asynchronously
await comObject.DoAsync();
```

Note that this example assumes that the original synchronous methods (`Connect` and `Do`) are thread-safe and can be safely executed on a separate thread.

